The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Sunday, August 29, 2004 				 Huge investment waves pound Orissa shores
 Spate of MoUs DEBABRATA MOHANTY				 	 Patnaik: Welcome gesture 																								Bhubaneswar, Aug. 28: Orissa seems to be on an MoU-signing spree, with four companies inking pacts with the state government for setting up sponge iron and mild steel plants last week. 																								The four companies that have signed MoUs are Maharashtra Seamless of Raigarh, Calcutta-based SPS Sponge Iron, Orissa Sponge Iron Limited and Sunflag Special Steels Ltd of Nagpur.																								The plants would be commissioned within the next three years. In the first phase, the four companies would invest around Rs 5,000 crore in the plants with an expected output of 5 million tonnes per annum.																								SPS Sponge Iron Ltd proposes to set up a Rs 400-crore sponge iron/steel-making project in Jharsuguda. The project will be set up in three phases. The first phase costing about Rs 62 crore is slated to go on stream by the end of September. The company intends to set up a 2.2-lakh-tonne sponge iron plant and then add a billet caster with a capacity of 2.6 lakh tonnes per annum for making steel in the second phase. The third phase comprises installation of blast furnace to produce 2 lakh tonnes of cold pig iron, a rolling mill to manufacture one lakh tonnes of finished products per annum and a 20 MW captive power plant. 																								Sunflag proposes to set up its one-million-tonne plant in Sambalpur district at an investment of Rs 937.19 crore . The first phase is likely to be commissioned in 2007. 																								Orissa Sponge Iron has proposed to invest Rs 1,037 crore in two phases for its plant at Gurla and Govindpur in Sambalpur district. The first phase of the plant would be commissioned in 2007. 																								Maharashtra Seamless has proposed to set up a 0.5-million-tonne steel billet plant at an investment of Rs 450 crore. 
